What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 Ford goBike rides in this dataset. The dataset has, initially, 16 features, such as:

  1. Numerical features:
    • duration_sec
    • start_station_id
    • start_station_latitude
    • start_station_longitude
    • end_station_id
    • end_station_latitude
    • end_station_longitude
    • bike_id
    • member_birth_year
  2. Categorical (object-typed) features:
    • user_type
    • member_gender
    • start_station_name
    • end_station_name
  3. Datetime features:
    • start_time
    • end_time
  4. Boolean features:
    • bike_share_for_all_trip

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features affect ride duration the most.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that age, gender, and user type will have the strongest effect on ride's duration. I don't think that 'bike_id' will help us in our analysis.

Some issues need to be fixed before exploring the dataset:¶

  • Drop rows with 'member_birth_year' and 'member_gender' missing data.
  • 'start_time' and 'end_time' columns need to be converted from object (string) dtype to datetime dtype.
  • 'bike_share_for_all_trip' column needs to be converted from object (string) dtype to boolean dtype.
  • Add a new column for member's age called 'member_age'. We can get it from the 'member_birth_year' column. It will be easier to deal with in our analysis.

Univariate Exploration¶

In [16]:
def univariate_plot(x, label, title, order= None):
    '''
    Plots a count plot of each unique value of a variable.
    
    Args
    ----
    x: Variable located on x-axis.
    label: The label of the x-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    order: Whether the values need to be ordered in a certain way or not.
    
    Return
    ------
    None
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize= (8, 6))
    if not order is None:
        sns.countplot(data= df, x= x, color= sns.color_palette()[0], order= order)
    else:
        sns.countplot(data= df, x= x, color= sns.color_palette()[0])
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(label)
    plt.show()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

While investigating, I found the duration column has some outliers that affect the study of the column. I had to cut off the last 0.5% of the values and neglect them. I thought to add a new column for the duration in minutes as it will ease the study due to the vast range in durations in seconds.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I added a column for member age by subtracting the birth year from current year. i.e. $year_{current} - year_{birth}$.
I also changed the dtype of 'start_time' and 'end_time' columns to datetime. That helped me to extract the ride's starting hour or day of week.

def bivariate_box_plot(x, y, title, xlabel, ylabel, color= 1):
    '''
    Plots boxplot between two variables.
    
    Args
    ----
    x: First variable. Located on x-axis.
    y: Second variable. Located on y-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    xlabel: The label of the x-axis.
    ylabel: The label of the y-axis.
    color: Index of a Seaborn's color-palette color.
    
    Return
    ------
    None
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize= (8, 6))

    sns.boxplot(data= df, x= x, y= y, color= sns.color_palette()[color])
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylim(0, 40)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)

    plt.show()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Trip duration depends on the member's age. Members aged between 30 and 40 years old have higher percentage of taking longer rides compared to other age ranges. While getting older, members are getting to take shorter rides. I can't tell that wasn't expected. As people age up, they can't do the same effort as before.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I thought that males in gender features will have the higher trip durations, but I found it is not the case. And for the user type feature, I thought that subscribers will have longer trips than the customers but it was also the opposite.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [39]:
def multivariate_plot(col, x, y, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    '''
    Plots scatter plot between two variables for each value of a third variable.
    
    Args
    ----
    col: The variable which we want to plot a scatter plot for every unique value of it.
    x: First variable. Located on x-axis.
    y: Second variable. Located on y-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    xlabel: The label of the x-axis.
    ylabel: The label of the y-axis.
    
    Return
    ------
    None
    '''
    col_wrap = len(df[col].value_counts())
    grid = sns.FacetGrid(data = df, col = col, col_wrap = col_wrap, size = 6,
                        xlim = [df[x].min() - 2, 85], ylim = [0, 400])

    grid.map(sns.scatterplot, x, y, alpha=0.3)
    grid.fig.suptitle(title)
    grid.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    grid.set_xlabels(xlabel)
    grid.set_ylabels(ylabel)

    plt.show()

There is a peak between 55~60 years old in 'Other' gender.
